, and the Critics, 28","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000643","text":"Mungo Park and the African Woman, 50","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000644","text":"Napoleon Bonaparte, 17, 18, 91, 110","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000645","text":"Neckar and the Corporation of Paris, 51","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000646","text":"Norton, Sir F. and Lord Mansfield, 72","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000647","text":"Old Age secured--the Irish Beggar, 11","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000648","text":"Ossuna, Duke of, and the Felon, 100","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000649","text":"Peterborough, Lord, and the Mob, 91","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000650","text":"Pitt, and the Duke of Newcastle, 86","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000651","text":"Pius IX., and the Attorney, 12","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000652","text":"Quartering upon the Enemy, 111","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000653","text":"Richardson--opinion of a Picture, 5","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000654","text":"Rivardes and the Wooden Leg, 111","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000655","text":"Scott, Sir W. --Punctuality, 99 and the Beggar, 11 and the Inn-keeper, 109","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000656","text":"Selwyn, G., and the Traveller, 116","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000657","text":"Sheridan, Dr., and the Scholar, 105","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000658","text":"Sion College, and George III., 131","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000659","text":"Smith, Sydney, Charity Sermon, 125","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000660","text":"Swift, Dean, 10, 21, 22, 109, 131","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000661","text":"Thomson the Poet, and Quin, 15","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000662","text":"Vernet--Picture of St. Jerome, 8","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000663","text":"Voisin, Chancellor of Louis XIX., 34","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000664","text":"Wager, Sir C., and the Doctors, 25","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000665","text":"Wardlaw, Archbishop of St. Andrew's, 49","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000666","text":"William III., and St. Evremond, 131","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000667","text":"Wise, Dr., and the Parliament, 131","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000668","text":"York, Duke of, and the Housekeeper, 108","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000669","text":"Amour.--This officer, who distinguished himself in the Imperial service, was the son of a poor Piedmontese peasant, but he never forgot his humble extraction.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000670","text":"While the army was in Piedmont, he invited his principal officers to an entertainment, when his father happened to arrive just as they were sitting down to table.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000671","text":"This being announced to the general, he immediately rose, and stated to his guests his father's arrival.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000672","text":"He said he knew the respect he owed to them, but at the same time he hoped they would excuse him if he withdrew, and dined with his father in another room.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000673","text":"The Deaf and Dumb Mother.--The late Countess of Orkney, who died at an advanced age, was deaf and dumb, and was married in 1753 by signs.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000674","text":"She resided with her husband at his seat, Rostellan, near Cork.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000675","text":"Shortly after the birth of her first child, the nurse saw the mother cautiously approach the cradle in which the infant lay asleep, evidently full of some deep design.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000676","text":"Before the nurse could interpose to prevent what she believed would bring certain death to the sleeping and unconscious child, the dreadful stone was flung, not at the cradle, however, but upon the ground, and fell with great violence.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000677","text":"The Countess was overjoyed, and, in the fulness of a mother's heart, she fell upon her knees to express her thankfulness that her beloved infant possessed a blessing denied to herself--the sense of hearing.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:gratitude","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000678","text":"This lady often gave similar indications of superior intelligence, though we can believe that few of them equalled the present in interest.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000679","text":"Filial Affection.--A veteran, worn out in the service of France, was left without a pension, although he had a wife and three children to share his wretchedness.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000680","text":"His son was placed at _L'Ecole militaire_, where he might have enjoyed every comfort, but the strongest persuasion could not induce him to taste anything but coarse bread and water.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000681","text":"The Duke de Choiseul being informed of the circumstance, ordered the boy before him, and enquired the reason of his abstemiousness.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000682","text":"The boy, with a manly fortitude, replied, \"Sir, when I had the honour of being admitted to this royal foundation, my father conducted me hither.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000683","text":"We came on foot: on our journey the demands of nature were relieved by bread and water.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000684","text":"My father blessed me, and returned to the protection of a helpless wife and family.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000685","text":"As long as I can remember, bread of the blackest kind, with water, has been their daily subsistence, and even that is earned by every species of labour that honour does not forbid.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000686","text":"The boy begged the louis d'ors might be sent to his father, which, with the patent of his pension, was immediately done.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000687","text":"The boy was patronised by the duke, and became one of the best officers in the service of France.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000688","text":"Racine.--The celebrated French poet, Racine, having one day returned from Versailles, where he had been on a visit, was waited upon by a gentleman with an invitation to dine at the Hotel de Condé.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000689","text":"Touching Recognition.--Some years ago, in making a new communication between two shafts of a mine at Fahkin, the capital of Delecarlia, the body of a miner was discovered by the workmen in a state of perfect preservation, and impregnated with vitriolic water.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000690","text":"It was quite soft, but hardened on being exposed to the air.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000691","text":"No one could identify the body: it was merely remembered that the accident, by which he had thus been buried in the bosom of the earth, had taken place above fifty years ago.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000692","text":"All enquiries about the name of the sufferer had already ceased, when a decrepid old woman, supported on crutches, slowly advanced towards the corpse, and knew it to be that of a young man to whom she had been promised in marriage more than half a century ago.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000693","text":"She threw herself on the corpse, which had all the appearance of a bronze statue, bathed it with her tears, and fainted with joy at having once more beheld the object of her affections.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000694","text":"One can with difficulty realize the singular contrast afforded by that couple--the one buried above fifty years ago, still retaining the appearance of youth; while the other, weighed down by age, evinced all the fervency of youthful affections.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000695","text":"Family Sacrifice.--During the French revolution, Madame Saintmaraule, with her daughter, and a youth, her son, not yet of age, were confined in prison and brought to trial.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000696","text":"The mother and daughter behaved with resolution, and were sentenced to die; but of the youth no notice was taken, and he was remanded to prison.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000697","text":"\"What!\" exclaimed the boy, \"am I then to be separated from my mother?","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000698","text":"It cannot be!\" and immediately he cried out, \"_Vive le Roi!_\" In consequence of this, he was condemned to death, and, with his mother and his sister, was led out to execution.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000699","text":"Expedient of Conjugal Affection.--Napoleon used to relate an anecdote shewing the conjugal affection of some women who accompanied his troops when he was at Col de Tende.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000700","text":"To enter this mountainous and difficult country, it was necessary for the soldiers to pass over a narrow bridge, and, as the enterprise was a hazardous one, Napoleon had given orders that no women should be permitted to cross it with them.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000701","text":"To enforce this order, two captains were stationed on the bridge with instructions, on pain of death, not to suffer a woman to pass.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mortality","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000702","text":"The passage was effected, and the troops continued their march.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000703","text":"When some miles beyond the bridge, the Emperor was greatly astonished at the appearance of a considerable number of women with the soldiers.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000704","text":"He immediately ordered the two captains to be put under arrest, intending to have them tried for a breach of duty.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000705","text":"The prisoners protested their innocence, and stoutly asserted that no women had crossed the bridge.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000706","text":"Napoleon, on hearing this, commanded that some of the women should be brought before him, when he interrogated them on the subject.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000707","text":"To his utter surprise they readily acknowledged that the captains had not betrayed their trust, but that a contrivance of their own had brought them into their present situation.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:relationships","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000708","text":"They informed Napoleon, that having taken the provisions, which had been prepared for the support of the army, out of some of the casks, they had concealed themselves in them, and by this stratagem succeeded in passing the bridge without discovery.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000709","text":"Sir Joshua Reynolds.--\"What do you ask for this sketch?\" said Sir Joshua to an old picture-dealer, whose portfolio he was looking over.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000710","text":"Richardson, in his anecdotes of painting, says, a gentleman came to me to invite me to his house: \"I have,\" says he, \"a picture of Rubens, and it is a rare good one.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000711","text":"the other day came to see it, and says it is _a copy_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000712","text":"If any one says so again, I'll _break his head_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000713","text":"Richardson, will you do me the favour to come, and give me _your real opinion of it?_\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000714","text":"Gainsborough.--A countryman was shown Gainsborough's celebrated picture of \"The Pigs.\" \"To be sure,\" said he, \"they be deadly like pigs; but there is one fault; nobody ever saw three pigs feeding together but what one on 'em had a foot in the trough.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000715","text":"Turner.--Once, at a dinner, where several artists, amateurs and literary men were convened, a poet, by way of being facetious, proposed as a toast the health of the _painters and glaziers_ of Great Britain.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:mental-health","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000716","text":"The toast was drunk, and Turner, after returning thanks for it, proposed the health of the British _paper-stainers_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mental-health","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000717","text":"Lely and the Alderman.--Sir Peter Lely, a famous painter in the reign of Charles I., agreed for the price of a full-length, which he was to draw for a rich alderman of London, who was not indebted to nature either for shape or face.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000718","text":"When the picture was finished, the alderman endeavoured to beat down the price; alleging that if he did not purchase it, it would lie on the painter's hands.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000719","text":"Morland.--It is well known that Morland the painter used to go on an expedition with a companion sometimes without a guinea, or perhaps scarcely a shilling, to defray the expenses of their journey; and thus they were often reduced to an unpleasant and ludicrous dilemma.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000720","text":"On one occasion the painter was travelling in Kent, in company with a relative, and finding their cash exhausted, while at a distance from their destination, they were compelled to exert their wits, for the purpose of recruiting themselves after a long and fatiguing march.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000721","text":"As they approached Canterbury, a homely village ale-house caught their eye; and the itinerant artists hailed, with delight, the sign of the Black Bull, which indicated abundance of home-made bread and generous ale.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000722","text":"They entered, and soon made considerable havoc among the good things of mine host, who, on reckoning up, found that they had consumed as much bread, cheese and ale, as amounted to _12s.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000723","text":"6d._ Morland now candidly informed his host that they were two poor painters going in search of employment, and that they had spent all their money.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000724","text":"He, however, added that, as the sign of the Bull was a disgraceful daub for so respectable a house, he would have no objection to repaint it, as a set-off for what he and his companion had received.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000725","text":"The landlord, who had long been wishing for a new sign (the one in question having passed through two generations), gladly accepted his terms, and Morland immediately went to work.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000726","text":"The next day the Bull was sketched in such a masterly manner that the landlord was enraptured; he supplied his guests with more provisions, and generously gave them money for their subsequent expenses.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000727","text":"In short, he purchased the sign of him for twenty pounds; the landlord was struck with admiration at his liberality; but this identical painting was some time afterwards sold at a public auction for the sum of _one hundred guineas!_","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000728","text":"When Benjamin West was seven years old, he was left, one summer day, with the charge of an infant niece.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000729","text":"As it lay in the cradle and he was engaged in fanning away the flies, the motion of the fan pleased the child, and caused it to smile.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000730","text":"Attracted by the charms thus created, young West felt his instinctive passion aroused; and seeing paper, pen and some red and black ink on a table, he eagerly seized them and made his first attempt at portrait painting.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000731","text":"Just as he had finished his maiden task, his mother and sister entered.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000732","text":"He tried to conceal what he had done, but his confusion arrested his mother's attention, and she asked him what he had been doing.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000733","text":"With reluctance and timidity, he handed her the paper, begging, at the same time, that she would not be offended.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000734","text":"The next year a cousin sent him a box of colours and pencils, with large quantities of canvas prepared for the easel, and half a dozen engravings.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism","tradition:zen"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000735","text":"Early the next morning he took his materials into the garret, and for several days forgot all about school.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000736","text":"His mother suspected that the box was the cause of his neglect of his books, and going into the garret and finding him busy at a picture, she was about to reprimand him; but her eye fell on some of his compositions, and her anger cooled at once.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000737","text":"She was so pleased with them that she loaded him with kisses, and promised to secure his father's pardon for his neglect of school.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000738","text":"The world is much indebted to Mrs.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000739","text":"West for her early and constant encouragement of the talent of her son.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:courage","theme:love","theme:resilience","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000740","text":"He often used to say, after his reputation was established, \"_My mothers kiss made me a painter!_\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000741","text":"Vernet relates, that he was once employed to paint a landscape, with a cave, and St.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000742","text":"Jerome in it; he accordingly painted the landscape with St.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000743","text":"Jerome at the entrance of the cave.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000744","text":"When he delivered the picture, the purchaser, who understood nothing of perspective, said, \"the landscape and the cave are well made, but St.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000745","text":"Jerome is not _in_ the cave.\"--\"I understand you, sir,\" replied Vernet, \"I will alter it.\" He therefore took the painting, and made the shade darker, so that the saint seemed to sit farther in.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000746","text":"The gentleman took the painting; but it again appeared to him that the saint was not actually in the cave.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000747","text":"Vernet then wiped out the figure, and gave it to the gentleman, who seemed perfectly satisfied.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000748","text":"Whenever he saw strangers to whom he showed the picture, he said, \"Here you see a picture by Vernet, with St.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000749","text":"Jerome in the cave.\" \"But we cannot see the saint,\" replied the visitors.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000750","text":"\"Excuse me, gentlemen,\" answered the possessor, \"he is there; for I saw him standing at the entrance, and afterwards farther back; and am therefore quite sure that he is in it.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000751","text":"Hogarth.--A nobleman, not remarkable for generosity, sent for Hogarth and desired that he would represent on one of the compartments of his staircase, Pharoah and his host drowned in the Red Sea.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000752","text":"At the same time he hinted that no great price would be given for the performance.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000753","text":"Soon afterwards he applied for payment to his employer, who seeing that the space allotted for the picture had only been daubed over with red, declared he had no idea of paying a painter when he had proceeded no farther than to lay his ground.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000754","text":"\"Ground!\" exclaimed Hogarth, \"there is no _ground_ in the case, my lord, it is all sea.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000755","text":"The red you perceive is the Red Sea.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000756","text":"Pharoah and his host are drowned as you desired, and cannot be made objects of sight, for the sea covers them all.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000757","text":"Tantara, the celebrated landscape painter, was a man of ready wit, but he once met his match.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000758","text":"An amateur had ordered a landscape for his gallery, in which there was to be a church.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000759","text":"Our painter did not know how to draw figures well, so he put none in the landscape.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000760","text":"The amateur was astonished at the truthfulness and colouring of the picture, but he missed the figures.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:truth","theme:wisdom","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000761","text":"\"You have forgotten to put in any figures,\" said he, laughingly.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000762","text":"\"Sir,\" replied the painter, \"_the people are gone to mass_.\" \"Oh, well,\" replied the amateur, \"I will wait and take your picture _when they come out_.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000763","text":"Chantrey's First Sculpture.--Chantrey, when a boy, used to take milk to Sheffield on an ass.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000764","text":"To those not used to seeing and observing such things, it may be necessary to state that the boys generally carry a good thick stick, with a hooked or knobbed end, with which they belabour their asses sometimes unmercifully.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000765","text":"On this, the gentleman asked to see what he had done, pronounced it to be an excellent likeness, and presented the youth with _sixpence_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000766","text":"This may, perhaps, be reckoned the first money Chantry ever obtained in the way of his _art_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000767","text":"Admiral Chatillon had gone one day to hear mass in the Dominican Friars' chapel; a poor fellow came and begged his charity.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000768","text":"He was at the moment occupied with his devotions, and he gave him several pieces of gold from his pocket, without counting them, or thinking what they were.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000769","text":"The large amount astonished the beggar, and as M.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000770","text":"A Beggar's Wedding.--Dean Swift being in the country, on a visit to Dr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000771","text":"Sheridan, they were informed that a beggar's wedding was about to be celebrated.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000772","text":"Sheridan played well upon the violin; Swift therefore proposed that he should go to the place where the ceremony was to be performed, disguised as a blind fiddler, while he attended him as his man.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000773","text":"Thus accoutred they set out, and were received by the jovial crew with great acclamation.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000774","text":"They had plenty of good cheer, and never was a more joyous wedding seen.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000775","text":"All was mirth and frolic; the beggars told stories, played tricks, cracked jokes, sung and danced, in a manner which afforded high amusement to the fiddler and his man, who were well rewarded when they departed, which was not till late in the evening.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000776","text":"The next day the Dean and Sheridan walked out in their usual dress, and found many of their late companions, hopping about upon crutches, or pretending to be blind, pouring forth melancholy complaints and supplications for charity.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000777","text":"Sheridan distributed among them the money he had received; but the Dean, who hated all mendicants, fell into a violent passion, telling them of his adventure of the preceding day, and threatening to send every one of them to prison.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000778","text":"This had such an effect, that the blind opened their eyes, and the lame threw away their crutches, running away as fast as their legs could carry them.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000779","text":"Old Age Secured.--As Sir Walter Scott was riding once with a friend in the neighbourhood of Abbotsford, he came to a field gate, which an Irish beggar who happened to be near hastened to open for him.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000780","text":"Sir Walter was desirous of rewarding his civility by the present of sixpence, but found that he had not so small a coin in his purse.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000781","text":"\"Here, my good fellow,\" said the baronet, \"here is a shilling for you; but mind, you owe me sixpence.\" \"God bless your honour!\" exclaimed Pat: \"may your honour live till I pay you.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000782","text":"Maximilian I.--A beggar once asked alms of the Emperor Maximilian I., who bestowed upon him a small coin.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000783","text":"The beggar appeared dissatisfied with the smallness of the gift, and on being asked why, he replied that it was a very little sum for an emperor, and that his highness should remember that we were all descended from one father, and were therefore all _brothers_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000784","text":"Maximilian smiled good-humouredly, and replied: \"Go--go, my good man: if each of your brothers gives you as much as I have done, you will very soon be far richer than me.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000785","text":"A Benevolent Judge.--The celebrated Anthony Domat, author of a treatise on the civil laws, was promoted to the office of judge of the provincial court of Clermont, in the territory of Auvergne, in the south of France.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000786","text":"In this court he presided, with general applause, for twenty-four years.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000787","text":"One day a poor widow brought an action against the Baron de Nairac, her landlord, for turning her out of her mill, which was the poor creature's sole dependence.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000788","text":"Nairac being inexorable, the judge was compelled to pronounce an ejectment, with the penalty mentioned in the lease and costs of suit; but he could not pronounce the decree without tears.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000789","text":"When an order of seizure, both of person and effects was added, the poor widow exclaimed, \"O merciful and righteous God, be thou a friend to the widow and her helpless orphans!\" and immediately fainted away.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000790","text":"The poor widow anxiously enquired of M.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000791","text":"Domat when he would require payment, that she might lay up accordingly.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000792","text":"\"When my conscience (he replied) shall tell me that I have done an improper act.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000793","text":"Pope Pius IX.--An advocate, the father of a large family, fell into ill health, and soon afterwards into want.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mental-health","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000794","text":"Pius IX., hearing of this, sent a messenger with a letter to the advocate, but he was at first refused admittance, on the ground that the physician had enjoined the utmost quiet.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000795","text":"On the messenger explaining from whom he came he was admitted, and, on the letter being opened, what was the surprise of the family on finding within 300 scudi (£62), with the words, \"For the advocate ...--Pius IX.,\" in the pontiff's own handwriting.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:love","theme:relationships","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000796","text":"Glynn was remarkable for many acts of kindness to poor persons.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000797","text":"He had attended a sick family in the fens near Cambridge for a considerable time, and had never thought of any recompense for his skill and trouble but the satisfaction of being able to do good.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000798","text":"One day he heard a noise on the college staircase, and his servant brought him word that the poor woman from the fens waited upon him with a _magpie_, of which she begged his acceptance.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:leadership","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000799","text":"This at first a little discomposed the doctor.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000800","text":"Of all presents, a magpie was the least acceptable to him, as he had a hundred loose things about his rooms, which the bird, if admitted, was likely to make free with.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000801","text":"However, his good nature soon returned: he considered the woman's intention, and ordered her to be shown in.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000802","text":"\"I am obliged to you for thinking of me, good woman,\" said he, \"but you must excuse my not taking your bird, as it would occasion me a great deal of trouble.\" \"Pray, doctor,\" answered the woman, \"do, pray, be pleased to have it.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000803","text":"My husband, my son, and myself have been long consulting together in what way we could show our thankfulness to you, and we could think of nothing better than to give you our favourite bird.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000804","text":"We would not part with it to any other person upon earth.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:animism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000805","text":"We shall be sadly hurt if you refuse our present.\" \"Well, well, my good woman,\" said Dr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000806","text":"Glynn, \"if that is the case, I must have the bird; but do you, as you say you are so fond of it, take it back again, and keep it for me, and I will allow you eighteenpence a week for the care of it.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000807","text":"I shall have the pleasure of seeing it every time I come.\" This allowance Dr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000808","text":"punctually paid as long as the bird lived.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000809","text":"An Odd Fault.--It is said that when the learned Humphrey Prideaux offered his Life of Mahomet to the bookseller, he was desired to leave the copy with him for a few days, for his perusal.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000810","text":"The bookseller said to the doctor at his return, \"Well, Mr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000811","text":"Johnson, while compiling his dictionary, sent a note to the _Gentleman's Magazine_, to inquire the etymology of the word CURMUDGEON.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000812","text":"Having obtained the desired information, he thus recorded in his work his obligation to an anonymous writer: \"CURMUDGEON, _s._ a vicious way of pronouncing _coeur mechant_.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000813","text":"An unknown correspondent.\" Ash copied the word into his dictionary, in the following manner: CURMUDGEON, from the French, _coeur_, \"unknown,\" and _mechant_, \"correspondent!\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:confucianism","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000814","text":"Heber's Palestine.--When Reginald Heber read his prize poem, \"Palestine,\" to Sir Walter Scott, the latter observed that, in the verses on Solomon's Temple, one striking circumstance had escaped him, namely, that no tools were used in its erection.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000815","text":"Reginald retired for a few minutes to the corner of the room, and returned with the beautiful lines:--","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000816","text":"\"No hammer fell, no ponderous axes rung; Like some tall palm, the mystic fabric sprung. Majestic silence,\" &c.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000817","text":"Use of H.--\"What has become of your famous General _Eel?_\" said the Count d'Erleon to Mr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000818","text":"\"Eel,\" said a bystander, \"that is a military fish I never heard of;\" but another at once enlightened his mind by saying to the count, \"General Lord _Hill_ is now Commander-in-Chief of the British forces!\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:christianity","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000819","text":"Cowper's \"John Gilpin.\"--It happened one afternoon, in those years when Cowper's accomplished friend, Lady Austen, made a part of his little evening circle, that she observed him sinking into increased dejection.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000820","text":"Its effects on the fancy of Cowper had the air of enchantment.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000821","text":"He informed her the next morning that convulsions of laughter, brought on by his recollection of her story, had kept him waking during the greatest part of the night!","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","audience:morning","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000822","text":"and that he had turned it into a ballad.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000823","text":"So arose the pleasant poem of \"John Gilpin.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000824","text":"of his _Literary Anecdotes_, mentions that Dr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000825","text":"Dickens' Origin of \"Boz.\"--A fellow passenger with Mr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000826","text":"Dickens, in the _Britannia_ steam-ship, across the Atlantic, inquired of the author the origin of his signature \"Boz.\" Mr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000827","text":"Dickens replied that he had a little brother who resembled so much the Moses in the _Vicar of Wakefield_, that he used to call him Moses also; but a younger girl, who could not then articulate plainly, was in the habit of calling him Bozie or Boz.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000828","text":"This simple circumstance made him assume that name in the first article he risked before the public, and as the first effort was approved of he continued the name.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000829","text":"Thomson and Quin.--Thomson the poet, when he first came to London, was in very narrow circumstances, and was many times put to shifts even for a dinner.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000830","text":"Upon the publication of his Seasons one of his creditors arrested him, thinking that a proper opportunity to get his money.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000831","text":"The report of this misfortune reached the ears of Quin, who had read the Seasons, but never seen their author; and he was told that Thompson was in a spunging-house in Holborn.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000832","text":"Quin then told him he was come to sup with him, and that he had already ordered the cook to provide supper, which he hoped he would excuse.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000833","text":"When supper was over, and the glass had gone briskly about, Mr.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000834","text":"Quin told him, \"It was now time to enter upon business.\" Thomson declared he was ready to serve him as far as his capacity would reach, in anything he should command, (thinking he was come about some affair relating to the drama).","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000835","text":"\"Sir,\" says Quin, \"you mistake me.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000836","text":"I owe you a hundred pounds, and I am come to pay you.\" Thomson, with a disconsolate air, replied, that, as he was a gentleman whom he had never offended, he wondered he should seek an opportunity to jest with his misfortunes.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:beauty","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000837","text":"\"No,\" said Quin, raising his voice, \"I say I owe you a hundred pounds, and there it is,\" (laying a bank note of that value before him).","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000838","text":"Thomson, astonished, begged he would explain himself.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000839","text":"Thomson, is my business.\" Of course Thomson left the house in company with his benefactor.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000840","text":"de Talleyrand, having one day invited M.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000841","text":"Denon, the celebrated traveller, to dine with him, told his wife to read the work of his guest, which she would find in the library, in order that she might be the better able to converse with him.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:productivity","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000842","text":"Madame Talleyrand, unluckily, got hold, by mistake, of the \"Adventures of Robinson Crusoe,\" by De Foe, which she ran over in great haste; and, at dinner, she began to question Denon about his shipwreck, his island, &c., and, finally, about his man Friday!","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000843","text":"Polignac.--Monsieur le Compte de Polignac had been raised to honour by Bonaparte; but, from some unaccountable motive, betrayed the trust his patron reposed in him.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","theme:relationships","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000844","text":"As soon as Bonaparte discovered the perfidy, he ordered Polignac to be put under arrest.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000845","text":"Next day he was to have been tried, and in all probability would have been condemned, as his guilt was undoubted.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000846","text":"In the meantime, Madame Polignac solicited and obtained an audience of the Emperor.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000847","text":"\"I am sorry, madam, for your sake,\" said he, \"that your husband has been implicated in an affair which is marked throughout with such deep ingratitude.\" \"He may not have been so guilty as your majesty supposes,\" said the countess.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:gratitude","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000848","text":"\"Do you know your husband's signature?\" asked the Emperor, as he took a letter from his pocket and presented it to her.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:mindfulness","theme:nature","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000849","text":"Madame de Polignac hastily glanced over the letter, recognised the writing, and fainted.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000850","text":"As soon as she recovered, Bonaparte, offering her the letter, said, \"Take it; it is the only legal evidence against your husband: there is a fire beside you.\" Madame de P.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","audience:recovery","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000851","text":"eagerly seized the important document, and in an instant committed it to the flames.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000852","text":"The life of Polignac was saved: his honour it was beyond the power even of the generosity of an emperor to redeem.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000853","text":"The Price of Bread.--Some years ago, the bakers of Lyons thought they could prevail on M.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000854","text":"Dugas, the provost of the merchants in that city, to befriend them at the expense of the public.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000855","text":"They waited upon him in a body, and begged leave to raise the price of bread, which could not be done without the sanction of the chief magistrate.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000856","text":"Dugas told them that he would examine their petition, and give them an early answer.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000857","text":"The bakers retired, having first left upon the table a purse of two hundred louis d'ors.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000858","text":"In a few days the bakers called upon the magistrate for an answer, not in the least doubting but that the money had effectually pleaded their cause.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000859","text":"Dugas, \"I have weighed your reasons in the balance of justice, and I find them light.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:justice","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000860","text":"I do not think that the people ought to suffer under a pretence of the dearness of corn, which I know to be unfounded; and as to the purse of money that you left with me, I am sure that I have made such a generous and noble use of it as you yourself intended.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","theme:self-knowledge","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000861","text":"I have distributed it among the poor objects of charity in our two hospitals.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000862","text":"As you are opulent enough to make such large donations, I cannot possibly think that you can incur any loss in your business; and I shall, therefore, continue the price of bread as it was.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:grief-healing","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:grief","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000863","text":"On his return, young Zeltner said that he never would ride his horse again unless he gave him his purse at the same time.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000864","text":"Mysterious Benefactor.--In the year 1720, celebrated for the bursting of the South Sea Bubble, a gentleman called late in the evening at the banking house of Messrs.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:evening","audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000865","text":"He was in a coach, but refused to get out, and desired that one of the partners of the house would come to him, into whose hands, when he appeared, he put a parcel, very carefully sealed up, and desired that it might be taken care of till he should call again.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:creativity","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000866","text":"A few days passed away--a few weeks--a few months--but the stranger never returned.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000867","text":"Bannister.--Charles Bannister dining one day at the Turk's Head Tavern, was much annoyed by a gentleman in the adjoining box, who had just ordered fish for dinner, and was calling on the waiter for every species of fish sauce known to the most refined epicure.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","theme:solitude","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000868","text":"\"Waiter,\" said he, \"bring me anchovy sauce, and soy; and have you got Harvey's?","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000869","text":"It will be good plum broth, however!\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000870","text":"Shortly afterwards, the doctor helped a gentleman to a slice of boiled leg of mutton, which was so far gone as to shed an odour not very agreeable to the noses of the company.","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."},{"id":"hafiz-ext-000871","text":"The gentleman repeatedly turned it upon his plate, without venturing to taste it; and the doctor observing him, said, \"Sir, perhaps you don't like mutton?\" \"Oh, yes, doctor,\" he replied, \"I am very fond of mutton, but I do not think the cook has boiled charcoal enough with it.\"","author":"Hafiz","source":"Poems from the Divan of Hafiz — Bell Translation","tags":["audience:meditation","language:en","theme:action","theme:love","tradition:sufism"],"isProverb":false,"isVerified":false,"verificationNote":"Auto-scraped; verify attribution and source citation."}]}